sec.p:
The genus SynhalcuriasCarlgren, 1914 was established to accommodate an actinernid sea anemone characterized by an oral disc without any lobes, IIyanthopsis elegansWassilieff, 1908 [= Synhalcurias elegans ( Wassilieff, 1908 )
]. Although having a rounded oral disc without lobes is common among most sea anemones, this simple shape is distinct within Actinernidae because the other three genera have more or less lobed oral discs ( Carlgren, 1949 ;
Izumi et al. , 2019
). N o additional species have been described in the century since the description of S. elegans ( Fautin, 2016 )
.

The holotype of Synhalcurias kahakui sp. nov. was collected off Otouto-Jima Island, Ogasawara Islands, in the Pacific Ocean (
), at 157 m depth on July 11, 2016 , using a biological dredge onboard the R/V Koyo of Tokyo Metropolitan Ogasawara Fisheries Research Center, Tokyo Metropolis. The specimen was kept relaxed in trays or tanks until the tentacles were completely extended, and then it was anesthetized with magnesium sulfate solution. The whole body, except for two tentacles, was fixed in 10% (v/v) formalin solution with seawater; the two tentacles were dissected and preserved in 99.5% ethanol. The paratypes of the new species were collected west off Amami O-shima Island, Nansei Islands, in the Pacific Ocean (
), at 315 m depth on May 23, 2019 , using a biological dredge onboard the R/V Toyoshio-Maru of Hiroshima University. The specimens were processed similarly to the holotype except for final preservation: two of three specimens were fixed whole in 10% (v/v) formalin solution with seawater, and the third whole one was preserved in 99% ethanol. The holotype and one paratype specimen were deposited in the National Museum of Nature and Science, Tokyo , NSMT (NSMT-Co 1695, 1696), and the other paratypes were deposited in the Coastal Branch of Natural History Museum and Institute, Chiba , CMNH (CMNH- ZG 09759, 09760).

Cnidae in the tentacles, column, actinopharynx, and filaments were observed and then photographed under differential interference contrast microscopy (referred to method of
Yanagi et al. , 2015
). Their length and width were measured on randomly chosen unexploded capsules using the software ImageJ v. 1.49 ( Rasband 1997 –2012). Cnidae nomenclature follows Mariscal (1974) .

