Material examined. Types (
). ZSM2004147 ( syntype ): specimen collected from Sagami Bay , Japan by Franz Doflein on May 1904 . ZSM2004148 ( syntype ): specimen collected from Sagami Bay , Japan , at 110 m , by Allan Owston using his yacht “Golden Hind” on July 24, 1902 . Other specimens (
).
NSMT-Co 1693: from Mikawa Bay , specimen dissected and fixed by Takato Izumi on June 1, 2016 . NSMT-Co 1694: collected January 2018 ,
at Uragami , Wakayama Prefecture , at 100–130 m , by Isao Hirabayashi , and dissected and fixed by Takuma Fujii and Kensuke Yanagi on May 22, 2018 .

Description . External anatomy .
Body cylindrical (
), 7–15 cm in length and 50–100 mm in diameter in living specimens, 50–100 mm in length and 35–80 mm in diameter in preserved specimens. Column surface relatively smooth, wrinkled but without any structures. Ectoderm of column pale orange or yellow when alive (
), with sparse, small nematocyst batteries. The naked column opaque milky white. Basal disc in aboral end, thick, robust and adhesive (
). Distal column not developed into lobes (
). Tentacles 76–100 in number on oral disc, all marginal, in two rows. All tentacles 5–10 mm in length, pale orange in color, long and slender without any structures and no thickenings. Tentacles less contractile and less adhesive. Oral disc pale orange, with radial stripes corresponding to every tentacle. Mouth at center of oral disc, lip-like, pale orange and yellow in color (
).

Internal anatomy
.

Perfect mesenteries 76-100, extending from distal to proximal ends; 
12 in
first cycle, including four directives; eight in second cycle; 
16 in
third cycle; and 
32 in
fourth cycle; fifth cycle incomplete. Mesenteries of second cycle in endocoels of mesenteries of first cycle, same as general arrangement of 
Actinernoidea
. Microcnemes absent (

). Tentacular longitudinal and circular muscles both too weak to observe in histological sections (

). Mesoglea on aboral ends of tentacles not thickened like 
Actinernus
. Retractor muscles extremely weak and diffuse (

); muscle processes too weak to count (

). Parietal muscles of mesenteries very weak and indistinct, with few muscle fibers (

). Mesoglea thickest in body wall and actinopharynx (

), 
2–5 mm
, far thicker than ectoderm and endoderm; mesoglea thinner in mesenteries (

) and basal disc, thinnest in tentacles. Two siphonoglyphs connected to actinopharynx on dorsal and ventral sides, with 18–22 longitudinal grooves (

). Marginal sphincter muscle and basilar muscles both absent. Dioecious: almost all mesenteries fertile, immature spermatic cysts in the specimens examined.

